metadata.name: SKYLIGHTS #211
metadata.description:
If you were trapped in a dream and looked up, what would you see?

---

Times of Day:
  • Day - Common
  • Dusk - Somewhat rare
  • Night - Rare

Moon:
  • Rare in Day + Dusk
  • Always present in Night

• Each time of day has its own soundscape
• Night pieces feature an easter-egg sound during a full moon

• Click anywhere, tap anything, or press any key to start the sound
• Press 's' to save a 4096x4096px frame of the piece
• Press 'f' to toggle fullscreen

---

metadata.name: Landfall #33
metadata.description:
Generative landscapes fall from the sky. Each minted artwork's unique expression and coloring is determined by a random seed hash and created live. 13 color palettes possible, heavily inspired by Japanese Ukiyo-e woodblock printing.

Series of 100

After generation is complete, right-click the canvas and 'save image as' to save in hi-res detail (3072x4096).

Artwork by 3dmanatee @3d_manatee. Made with p5js and ❤️

metadata.name: PsychoBeats #1
metadata.description:
3D + Sound ShockWave

A 3D randomly-generated object moving in space and distorted by a random audio shockwave.
You can launch the beat, pause it when you like, increase resolution up to 8K.
You can also go to static snapshot as rendered by fxhash platform.


Like it? Check its grand brother Beat'em Tone https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/8350.

WARNING: Webgl/GPU advised, CPU compliant but might lag, mobile lags more & crazy distortions.

Notice: If you click "key X" (static snapshot) and then Space to relaunch audio, it can take a few seconds to reinitialize audio context.

Controls:
- H: hide/show help.
- Dbl-Click - Space: start/pause animation for snapshots.
- Q/A - D: resolution down/up (720p, 1080p, 2K, 4K, 8K).
- S: Pause/Unpause animation.
- X: Static Snapshot.
- B - Export full resolution pix (up to 8K, link appears below, scroll down)
- I: hide/show info panel. Click for panels (info, FPS).

HypnoBeats @naibdian 2021 using Opensource WebGL, ReactJS, ThreeJS libs, Raymond Hill's Javascript Voronoi.

metadata.name: EPIHYPERDERPFLARDIOIDS #185
metadata.description:
EPIHYPERDERPFLARDIOIDS

after symbol 2525, 
aint gonna need to load, write no code
everything you think, do and say
is in the streams that you watch today (oh oh oh)

We find this code is very much alive. They are epi. They are hyper. They are derp. They are flardioids.

Epihyperderpflardioids is the name I have given to a large family of symmetrical loopy shapes, based on sine waves and rotations, reminiscent of the mathematical toy game "Spirograph", but also different. I studied them extensively, but don't claim to understand them fully, yet. I hope you enjoy them as much as I do.

These 365 Epihyperderpflardioids were generated for FXhash's one year anniversary.

metadata.name: Granular deconstruction #8
metadata.description:
Granular synthesizer.

Click on the canvas for the audio to start.

X-Axis: transpose tape head across the sample.
Y-Axis: amplitude.

fxhash features:
- sample (five samples are available)
- density of the played samples
- spread (offset around the played back portion)
- panning
- theme (small chance for different color)

metadata.name: Frozen Windows #16
metadata.description: Frozen Windows is inspired by the dendritic growth structure that arises when frost settles and spreads across a windowpane.

metadata.name: Dots #83
metadata.description:
Titled as a play with colors and shapes created from dots, Dots started as a collection on Objkt, extended to 8bidou and had new developments in Exchange Art. It was a dream to be able to make a collection of Dots on Fxhash, now it finally happened. Initially we only had 1 color palette, however, to create more variety, this project has 7 color palettes. To create the palettes we chose 5 famous artists to honor, including Peter Halley, Max Bill, Piet Mondrian, Sophie Taeuber and Lygia Clark, in addition to the palettes created by us. The project has several grids and some new possibilities in addition to the pieces already created on other platforms. It is with great pride and joy that we present this project made with great affection. Enjoy!

Press [S] to save a image

metadata.name: Dizzy v1.0 #1
metadata.description:
This is an experiment with color and animation along with trying to sort out how to use THREE.js to get the proper visual effects that I want. I'm letting this one out for free... resale royalties are split with THREE.js getting 5% of the resale to credit their contribution properly. Thanks for any feedback that you have (I am on Discourse under Vroomcrds#4688). Enjoy!!

Interactive with several user controls:

With the mouse:

Left click and drag to change the viewing angle
Right click and drag to change the view center
Mouse wheel to change the distance to the view center

With the keyboard:

Keys "," and "." (i.e. "<" and ">") change the rotation speed left or right. You can stop it entirely, or speed it up to what I consider a reasonable maximum, rotating to the left or to the right. Each time you press, it adjusts the rotation speed

Keys "a" "b" and "c": the lights always start in the same place, and each key controls one of the three lights, both position and intensity. It is deterministic from the initial start based upon the token: for a given token, after the initial run (or re-run) pressing "aaabbcabcabc" will give you the same sequence of lighting changes. This lets you choose your favorite and keep track of it.

metadata.name: Blurevich #231
metadata.description:
"Blurevich"

The painting is characterized by its non-representational style, where the rectangles are not meant to depict recognizable objects or figures. 
Instead, the blurred rectangles serve as visual elements that create a sense of movement and dynamism in the painting. 
The use of blurriness in the rectangles gives the painting a hazy and ethereal quality. 
The colors used in the painting would  be bold and striking, creating a striking contrast between the sharp edges of the rectangles and the soft, blurred edges. 
The overall effect of the painting is one of abstraction and experimentation, express our emotions.

metadata.name: The Wintertime #2
metadata.description:
"The Wintertime" is a collection of generative art that captures the essence of the winter season in a glitchy and abstract way. The pieces in this collection are a visual representation of the harshness and beauty of winter, where the cold and barren landscapes are juxtaposed against the sparkling snow and ice. The glitches and digital distortions in the art add a sense of chaos and unpredictability, mirroring the unpredictable nature of winter weather. The collection celebrates the winter season in all its raw and untamed glory. Each piece is unique and evocative, inviting the viewer to get lost in the beauty of the wintertime.

The work was inspired by the drip painting technique of Jackson Pollock and the minimalistic elegance of Japanese prints. Combining these two distinct styles creates a visually striking and thought-provoking collection that pays homage to the masters while pushing the boundaries of contemporary art.

This collection is the continuation of GPTree: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/17691

Genuary 2023: Recursive trees

metadata.name: Gkrint #159
metadata.description:
Gkrint is a celebration of minimalism, colour, and space using the humble grid, a foundation of generative art, and movement. Through this collaboration, Ballzerino and George explore the relationships between these elements.

Inspired by the timeless principles of Bauhaus design, Ballzerino carefully curated custom colour palettes and selected geometric shapes, while George encoded the creative process into an algorithm, bringing the compositions to life, and putting the CPU to work finding new and unexpected compositions within our framework.

Gkrint is Ballzerino's genesis generative art drop.

Controls:
SPACE - pause / resume
click (or tap) - change colour selection (within same palette)
hold 'f' - speed up animation

Tested on Windows / Mac / iOS / Android. Chrome recommended for the best experience.
